Certainly not. The creature simply whistled and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost her grip on its overly smooth scales.
"WHAT DID YOU DO TO HIM?" shouted Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!"
"IT'S NOT GOING TO BE EASY!"
Thassalin blew, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed, somewhat panicked when a bolt of fire struck her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed she was no longer alone. Her panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then struck her violently on the head with his tail, diverting her from her path.
Grumbling and hissing, the creature gained altitude and spat into the air. Suddenly, everything turned black, as if the monster were sucking the light from the sky and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
With no visibility left, Thassalin attempted to retreat, but crashed into the tops of the trees before falling into the clearing. As if she had known exactly where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in its wake.
"Kayel!" exclaimed Tenuk as he pulled himself out of the cloud and began flying in circles to try to spot Nyssi and Thassalin below in the darkness. "What are we doing, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi struggled to her feet as best she could. She was certain she had broken something, but her strange, unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. One could not say the same for Thassalin, who lay sprawled on a mound, leaning against the only tree that had not bent under his weight. Nyssi tried her best to reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see two meters ahead of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by sinister shadows. And within those shadows, something was howling.
A horrible club-like tail came crashing down beside Nyssi, knocking her backward. However, she noticed that the tail was swaying, not aiming at her. The creature, as much as Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and clawing at the shadows it had created. Something teleported through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A sudden gunshot rang out, and the monster collapsed in silence, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had happened. Standing atop the creature was Kayel, holding the gun and catching his breath.
"It's... the strangest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon..." gasped Kayel. His eyes glowed with a black light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, the organic plating on Kayel's body regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow hue.
It took Nyssi a moment to realize what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, since most people regarded them as impious and rather frightening. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed surprised as well.
"Are you okay?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk struggled to land next to him, regaining his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as charcoal and slimy, but the saliva continued to cling to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns emerged from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what that thing was, something screamed and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the creature didn't have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, hurling it to Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oops..." muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before clumsily turning off the engine and leaping from the truck. "I, um, didn't mean to do that. Are you okay?"
"Tenuk regretted, 'You practically missed the entire action,' 'Where were you?'"
"You all abandoned me. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can anyone tell me what these contemptible things are?"
Retrovik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut up and scratched all over, and seemed a bit confused, but he didn't look too badly hurt.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"Tou want to say... the horrible god-monster that we have... helped kill?" stammered Tenuk.
"YES. COMPLETELY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO HIT THEM IN THE HEAD. I'M LACKING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, THAT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked toward Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, KAYEL. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS ABLE TO DESTROY UNIVERSES."
"Euh... thanks... I guess," said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nissy shrugged, then picked up her camera to photograph the now-dead creatures. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the blade of the god of death, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns, then moved on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures caught fire and quickly turned into piles of ash. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
" Well... it's both convenient and entirely inconvenient," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
